Content: CHAPTER VI. Pig and Pepper

For a minute or two she stood looking at the house, and wondering what to do next, when suddenly a footman in livery came running out of the wood—(she considered him to be a footman because he was in livery: otherwise, judging by his face only, she would have called him a fish)—and rapped loudly at the door with his knuckles. It was opened by another footman in livery, with a round face, and large eyes like a frog; and both footmen, Alice noticed, had powdered hair that curled all over their heads. She felt very curious to know what it was all about, and crept a little way out of the wood to listen.
ESummary: Alice sees two footmen, one resembling a fish and the other a frog, and overhears them discussing an invitation for the Duchess from the Queen to play croquet.
CText: Alice stands looking at the house, pondering what to do next.

Content: The Fish-Footman began by producing from under his arm a great letter, nearly as large as himself, and this he handed over to the other, saying, in a solemn tone, “For the Duchess. An invitation from the Queen to play croquet.” The Frog-Footman repeated, in the same solemn tone, only changing the order of the words a little, “From the Queen. An invitation for the Duchess to play croquet.”
ESummary: Alice sees two footmen, one resembling a fish and the other a frog, and overhears them discussing an invitation for the Duchess from the Queen to play croquet.
CText: The Frog-Footman repeats the invitation from the Queen in a solemn tone.

Content: Then they both bowed low, and their curls got entangled together.

Alice laughed so much at this, that she had to run back into the wood for fear of their hearing her; and when she next peeped out the Fish-Footman was gone, and the other was sitting on the ground near the door, staring stupidly up into the sky.
CText: The Fish-Footman leaves abruptly, causing Alice to laugh.

Content: Alice went timidly up to the door, and knocked.
ESummary: Alice attempts to knock on the door but is informed by the Frog Footman that it would be futile, as he is on the same side of the door.

Content: “There’s no sort of use in knocking,” said the Footman, “and that for two reasons. First, because I’m on the same side of the door as you are; secondly, because they’re making such a noise inside, no one could possibly hear you.” And certainly there _was_ a most extraordinary noise going on within—a constant howling and sneezing, and every now and then a great crash, as if a dish or kettle had been broken to pieces.
ESummary: Alice attempts to knock on the door but is informed by the Frog Footman that it would be futile, as he is on the same side of the door.

Content: “Please, then,” said Alice, “how am I to get in?”
ESummary: Alice attempts to knock on the door but is informed by the Frog Footman that it would be futile, as he is on the same side of the door.

Content: “There might be some sense in your knocking,” the Footman went on without attending to her, “if we had the door between us. For instance, if you were _inside_, you might knock, and I could let you out, you know.” He was looking up into the sky all the time he was speaking, and this Alice thought decidedly uncivil. “But perhaps he can’t help it,” she said to herself; “his eyes are so _very_ nearly at the top of his head. But at any rate he might answer questions.—How am I to get in?” she repeated, aloud.
ESummary: Alice attempts to knock on the door but is informed by the Frog Footman that it would be futile, as he is on the same side of the door.

Content: “I shall sit here,” the Footman remarked, “till tomorrow—”
ESummary: Alice attempts to knock on the door but is informed by the Frog Footman that it would be futile, as he is on the same side of the door.

Content: At this moment the door of the house opened, and a large plate came skimming out, straight at the Footman’s head: it just grazed his nose, and broke to pieces against one of the trees behind him.
Event: Alice attempts to enter the house

Content: “—or next day, maybe,” the Footman continued in the same tone, exactly as if nothing had happened.
CText: The Frog-Footman sits staring stupidly after the Fish-Footman leaves.

Content: “How am I to get in?” asked Alice again, in a louder tone.
“_Are_ you to get in at all?” said the Footman. “That’s the first question, you know.”
It was, no doubt: only Alice did not like to be told so. “It’s really dreadful,” she muttered to herself, “the way all the creatures argue. It’s enough to drive one crazy!”
The Footman seemed to think this a good opportunity for repeating his remark, with variations. “I shall sit here,” he said, “on and off, for days and days.”
“But what am _I_ to do?” said Alice.
“Anything you like,” said the Footman, and began whistling.
“Oh, there’s no use in talking to him,” said Alice desperately: “he’s perfectly idiotic!” And she opened the door and went in.

The door led right into a large kitchen, which was full of smoke from one end to the other: the Duchess was sitting on a three-legged stool in the middle, nursing a baby; the cook was leaning over the fire, stirring a large cauldron which seemed to be full of soup.
ESummary: Alice finally enters the kitchen, filled with smoke and chaos, where the Duchess is nursing a baby amidst a tumult created by the cook.

Content: “There’s certainly too much pepper in that soup!” Alice said to herself, as well as she could for sneezing.
ESummary: Alice finally enters the kitchen, filled with smoke and chaos, where the Duchess is nursing a baby amidst a tumult created by the cook.
CText: The Duchess is stirring a cauldron of soup.

Content: There was certainly too much of it in the air. Even the Duchess sneezed occasionally; and as for the baby, it was sneezing and howling alternately without a moment’s pause. The only things in the kitchen that did not sneeze, were the cook, and a large cat which was sitting on the hearth and grinning from ear to ear.
“Please would you tell me,” said Alice, a little timidly, for she was not quite sure whether it was good manners for her to speak first, “why your cat grins like that?”
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: “It’s a Cheshire cat,” said the Duchess, “and that’s why. Pig!”
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: She said the last word with such sudden violence that Alice quite jumped; but she saw in another moment that it was addressed to the baby, and not to her, so she took courage, and went on again:—
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: “I didn’t know that Cheshire cats always grinned; in fact, I didn’t know that cats _could_ grin.”
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: “They all can,” said the Duchess; “and most of ’em do.”
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: “I don’t know of any that do,” Alice said very politely, feeling quite pleased to have got into a conversation.
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: “You don’t know much,” said the Duchess; “and that’s a fact.”
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.

Content: Alice did not at all like the tone of this remark, and thought it would be as well to introduce some other subject of conversation. While she was trying to fix on one, the cook took the cauldron of soup off the fire, and at once set to work throwing everything within her reach at the Duchess and the baby—the fire-irons came first; then followed a shower of saucepans, plates, and dishes. The Duchess took no notice of them even when they hit her; and the baby was howling so much already, that it was quite impossible to say whether the blows hurt it or not.
ESummary: Alice engages in a perplexing conversation with the Duchess about the Cheshire cat, leading to confusion with the Duchess’s abrupt behavior.
CText: The cook throws items at the Duchess and the baby.

Content: “Oh, _please_ mind what you’re doing!” cried Alice, jumping up and down in an agony of terror. “Oh, there goes his _precious_ nose!” as an unusually large saucepan flew close by it, and very nearly carried it off.
“If everybody minded their own business,” the Duchess said in a hoarse growl, “the world would go round a deal faster than it does.”

“Which would _not_ be an advantage,” said Alice, who felt very glad to get an opportunity of showing off a little of her knowledge. “Just think of what work it would make with the day and night! You see the earth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis—”
“Talking of axes,” said the Duchess, “chop off her head!”

Alice glanced rather anxiously at the cook, to see if she meant to take the hint; but the cook was busily stirring the soup, and seemed not to be listening, so she went on again: “Twenty-four hours, I _think_; or is it twelve? I—”

“Oh, don’t bother _me_,” said the Duchess; “I never could abide figures!” And with that she began nursing her child again, singing a sort of lullaby to it as she did so, and giving it a violent shake at the end of every line:
“Speak roughly to your little boy,     And beat him when he sneezes: He only does it to annoy,     Because he knows it teases.”
ESummary: The Duchess sings a strange lullaby to her baby while roughly handling it, highlighting her chaotic nature and the nonsensical environment Alice finds herself in.
CText: The Duchess sings a violent lullaby while shaking the baby.

Content: CHORUS. (In which the cook and the baby joined):
“Wow! wow! wow!”
While the Duchess sang the second verse of the song, she kept tossing the baby violently up and down, and the poor little thing howled so, that Alice could hardly hear the words:—
“I speak severely to my boy,     I beat him when he sneezes; For he can thoroughly enjoy     The pepper when he pleases!”
CHORUS.
“Wow! wow! wow!”

“Here! you may nurse it a bit, if you like!” the Duchess said to Alice, flinging the baby at her as she spoke. “I must go and get ready to play croquet with the Queen,” and she hurried out of the room. The cook threw a frying-pan after her as she went out, but it just missed her.
ESummary: The Duchess unexpectedly hands over the baby to Alice, who struggles to hold it as the chaotic scene continues with the cook throwing kitchenware.
CText: The Cook throws a frying pan at the Duchess as she departs.

Content: Alice caught the baby with some difficulty, as it was a queer-shaped little creature, and held out its arms and legs in all directions, “just like a star-fish,” thought Alice. The poor little thing was snorting like a steam-engine when she caught it, and kept doubling itself up and straightening itself out again, so that altogether, for the first minute or two, it was as much as she could do to hold it.
ESummary: The Duchess unexpectedly hands over the baby to Alice, who struggles to hold it as the chaotic scene continues with the cook throwing kitchenware.

Content: As soon as she had made out the proper way of nursing it, (which was to twist it up into a sort of knot, and then keep tight hold of its right ear and left foot, so as to prevent its undoing itself,) she carried it out into the open air. “If I don’t take this child away with me,” thought Alice, “they’re sure to kill it in a day or two: wouldn’t it be murder to leave it behind?” She said the last words out loud, and the little thing grunted in reply (it had left off sneezing by this time). “Don’t grunt,” said Alice; “that’s not at all a proper way of expressing yourself.”

The baby grunted again, and Alice looked very anxiously into its face to see what was the matter with it. There could be no doubt that it had a _very_ turn-up nose, much more like a snout than a real nose; also its eyes were getting extremely small for a baby: altogether Alice did not like the look of the thing at all. “But perhaps it was only sobbing,” she thought, and looked into its eyes again, to see if there were any tears.

No, there were no tears. “If you’re going to turn into a pig, my dear,” said Alice, seriously, “I’ll have nothing more to do with you. Mind now!” The poor little thing sobbed again (or grunted, it was impossible to say which), and they went on for some while in silence.

Alice was just beginning to think to herself, “Now, what am I to do with this creature when I get it home?” when it grunted again, so violently, that she looked down into its face in some alarm. This time there could be _no_ mistake about it: it was neither more nor less than a pig, and she felt that it would be quite absurd for her to carry it further.
Event: The baby turns into a pig
ESummary: Alice realizes that the baby she was holding has transformed into a pig, which she decides to release into the woods, reflecting on the absurdity of the situation.
CText: Alice realizes the baby has turned into a pig.

Content: So she set the little creature down, and felt quite relieved to see it trot away quietly into the wood. “If it had grown up,” she said to herself, “it would have made a dreadfully ugly child: but it makes rather a handsome pig, I think.” And she began thinking over other children she knew, who might do very well as pigs, and was just saying to herself, “if one only knew the right way to change them—” when she was a little startled by seeing the Cheshire Cat sitting on a bough of a tree a few yards off.
Event: The baby turns into a pig
ESummary: Alice realizes that the baby she was holding has transformed into a pig, which she decides to release into the woods, reflecting on the absurdity of the situation.

Content: The Cat only grinned when it saw Alice. It looked good-natured, she thought: still it had _very_ long claws and a great many teeth, so she felt that it ought to be treated with respect.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.
CText: The Cat grins at Alice from a tree branch.

Content: “Cheshire Puss,” she began, rather timidly, as she did not at all know whether it would like the name: however, it only grinned a little wider. “Come, it’s pleased so far,” thought Alice, and she went on. “Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “That depends a good deal on where you want to get to,” said the Cat.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “I don’t much care where—” said Alice.

Content: “Then it doesn’t matter which way you go,” said the Cat.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “—so long as I get _somewhere_,” Alice added as an explanation.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “Oh, you’re sure to do that,” said the Cat, “if you only walk long enough.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: Alice felt that this could not be denied, so she tried another question. “What sort of people live about here?”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “In _that_ direction,” the Cat said, waving its right paw round, “lives a Hatter: and in _that_ direction,” waving the other paw, “lives a March Hare. Visit either you like: they’re both mad.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “But I don’t want to go among mad people,” Alice remarked.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “Oh, you can’t help that,” said the Cat: “we’re all mad here. I’m mad. You’re mad.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “How do you know I’m mad?” said Alice.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “You must be,” said the Cat, “or you wouldn’t have come here.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: Alice didn’t think that proved it at all; however, she went on “And how do you know that you’re mad?”

Content: “To begin with,” said the Cat, “a dog’s not mad. You grant that?”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “I suppose so,” said Alice.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “Well, then,” the Cat went on, “you see, a dog growls when it’s angry, and wags its tail when it’s pleased. Now _I_ growl when I’m pleased, and wag my tail when I’m angry. Therefore I’m mad.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “_I_ call it purring, not growling,” said Alice.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “Call it what you like,” said the Cat. “Do you play croquet with the Queen to-day?”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “I should like it very much,” said Alice, “but I haven’t been invited yet.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who cryptically informs her about the madness of the inhabitants in Wonderland and offers guidance regarding her journey.

Content: “You’ll see me there,” said the Cat, and vanished.

Content: Alice was not much surprised at this, she was getting so used to queer things happening. While she was looking at the place where it had been, it suddenly appeared again.
“By-the-bye, what became of the baby?” said the Cat. “I’d nearly forgotten to ask.”
“It turned into a pig,” Alice quietly said, just as if it had come back in a natural way.
“I thought it would,” said the Cat, and vanished again.

Content: Alice waited a little, half expecting to see it again, but it did not appear, and after a minute or two she walked on in the direction in which the March Hare was said to live. “I’ve seen hatters before,” she said to herself; “the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and perhaps as this is May it won’t be raving mad—at least not so mad as it was in March.” As she said this, she looked up, and there was the Cat again, sitting on a branch of a tree.

Event: Alice decides to visit the March Hare

Content: “Well! I’ve often seen a cat without a grin,” thought Alice; “but a grin without a cat! It’s the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!”
Event: Alice decides to visit the March Hare

Content: She had not gone much farther before she came in sight of the house of the March Hare: she thought it must be the right house, because the chimneys were shaped like ears and the roof was thatched with fur. It was so large a house, that she did not like to go nearer till she had nibbled some more of the lefthand bit of mushroom, and raised herself to about two feet high: even then she walked up towards it rather timidly, saying to herself “Suppose it should be raving mad after all! I almost wish I’d gone to see the Hatter instead!”

Content: CHAPTER VII. A Mad Tea-Party

There was a table set out under a tree in front of the house, and the March Hare and the Hatter were having tea at it: a Dormouse was sitting between them, fast asleep, and the other two were using it as a cushion, resting their elbows on it, and talking over its head. “Very uncomfortable for the Dormouse,” thought Alice; “only, as it’s asleep, I suppose it doesn’t mind.”
ESummary: Alice stumbles upon the March Hare and the Hatter having tea with a Dormouse who is asleep. The Hatter and March Hare express that there's no room at the table, prompting Alice to sit down regardless. This sets the stage for the ensuing nonsensical and whimsical dialogue.
CText: The Dormouse was asleep between the March Hare and the Hatter.

Content: The table was a large one, but the three were all crowded together at one corner of it: “No room! No room!” they cried out when they saw Alice coming. “There’s _plenty_ of room!” said Alice indignantly, and she sat down in a large arm-chair at one end of the table.
ESummary: Alice stumbles upon the March Hare and the Hatter having tea with a Dormouse who is asleep. The Hatter and March Hare express that there's no room at the table, prompting Alice to sit down regardless. This sets the stage for the ensuing nonsensical and whimsical dialogue.

“Then it wasn’t very civil of you to offer it,” said Alice angrily.
CText: Alice angrily pointed out the March Hare's rudeness for offering wine that wasn't available.

Content: “I didn’t know it was _your_ table,” said Alice; “it’s laid for a great many more than three.”
“Your hair wants cutting,” said the Hatter. He had been looking at Alice for some time with great curiosity, and this was his first speech.
CText: The Hatter remarked that Alice's hair needed cutting.

Content: “You should learn not to make personal remarks,” Alice said with some severity; “it’s very rude.”

Content: “One, indeed!” said the Dormouse indignantly. However, he consented to go on. “And so these three little sisters—they were learning to draw, you know—”

Content: “What did they draw?” said Alice, quite forgetting her promise.
“Treacle,” said the Dormouse, without considering at all this time.
“I want a clean cup,” interrupted the Hatter: “let’s all move one place on.”

He moved on as he spoke, and the Dormouse followed him: the March Hare moved into the Dormouse’s place, and Alice rather unwillingly took the place of the March Hare. The Hatter was the only one who got any advantage from the change: and Alice was a good deal worse off than before, as the March Hare had just upset the milk-jug into his plate.
CText: The March Hare moved to a different place at the table for a clean cup.

Content: Alice did not wish to offend the Dormouse again, so she began very cautiously: “But I don’t understand. Where did they draw the treacle from?”
“You can draw water out of a water-well,” said the Hatter; “so I should think you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well—eh, stupid?”
“But they were _in_ the well,” Alice said to the Dormouse, not choosing to notice this last remark.
“Of course they were,” said the Dormouse; “—well in.”
This answer so confused poor Alice, that she let the Dormouse go on for some time without interrupting it.
“They were learning to draw,” the Dormouse went on, yawning and rubbing its eyes, for it was getting very sleepy; “and they drew all manner of things—everything that begins with an M—”
CText: The Dormouse began yawning and indicated it was getting sleepy.

Content: “Why with an M?” said Alice.
“Why not?” said the March Hare.
Alice was silent.

The Dormouse had closed its eyes by this time, and was going off into a doze; but, on being pinched by the Hatter, it woke up again with a little shriek, and went on: “—that begins with an M, such as mouse-traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness—you know you say things are “much of a muchness”—did you ever see such a thing as a drawing of a muchness?”
“Really, now you ask me,” said Alice, very much confused, “I don’t think—”
“Then you shouldn’t talk,” said the Hatter.
ESummary: As the conversation grows increasingly nonsensical, Alice becomes frustrated by the rudeness of the group, ultimately leading her to stand up and leave the tea party.
CText: The Hatter rudely told Alice she shouldn't talk if she didn't have anything to say.

Content: This piece of rudeness was more than Alice could bear: she got up in great disgust, and walked off; the Dormouse fell asleep instantly, and neither of the others took the least notice of her going, though she looked back once or twice, half hoping that they would call after her: the last time she saw them, they were trying to put the Dormouse into the teapot.
ESummary: Frustrated by the nonsensical discussion and rudeness, Alice gets up and leaves the tea party, realizing how absurd everything has been. This moment marks her desire to seek something more meaningful.

Content: “At any rate I’ll never go _there_ again!” said Alice as she picked her way through the wood. “It’s the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in all my life!”
ESummary: Frustrated by the nonsensical discussion and rudeness, Alice gets up and leaves the tea party, realizing how absurd everything has been. This moment marks her desire to seek something more meaningful.

Content: Just as she said this, she noticed that one of the trees had a door leading right into it. “That’s very curious!” she thought. “But everything’s curious today. I think I may as well go in at once.” And in she went.
ESummary: Alice discovers a door in a tree and decides to enter, leading her back to the magical garden she longs for. This signifies a new beginning for her adventures in Wonderland.

Content: Once more she found herself in the long hall, and close to the little glass table. “Now, I’ll manage better this time,” she said to herself, and began by taking the little golden key, and unlocking the door that led into the garden. Then she went to work nibbling at the mushroom (she had kept a piece of it in her pocket) till she was about a foot high: then she walked down the little passage: and _then_—she found herself at last in the beautiful garden, among the bright flower-beds and the cool fountains.
ESummary: Alice discovers a door in a tree and decides to enter, leading her back to the magical garden she longs for. This signifies a new beginning for her adventures in Wonderland.

Content: CHAPTER VIII. The Queen’s Croquet-Ground

A large rose-tree stood near the entrance of the garden: the roses growing on it were white, but there were three gardeners at it, busily painting them red. Alice thought this a very curious thing, and she went nearer to watch them, and just as she came up to them she heard one of them say, “Look out now, Five! Don’t go splashing paint over me like that!”
Event: Alice witnesses the gardeners painting roses
ESummary: Alice encounters three gardeners frantically painting white roses red to avoid the Queen's wrath for having mistakenly planted a white rose. This strangely comical scene introduces the concept of fear and absurdity in the court.

Content: “Would you tell me,” said Alice, a little timidly, “why you are painting those roses?”

Content: Five and Seven said nothing, but looked at Two. Two began in a low voice, “Why the fact is, you see, Miss, this here ought to have been a _red_ rose-tree, and we put a white one in by mistake; and if the Queen was to find it out, we should all have our heads cut off, you know. So you see, Miss, we’re doing our best, afore she comes, to—” At this moment Five, who had been anxiously looking across the garden, called out “The Queen! The Queen!” and the three gardeners instantly threw themselves flat upon their faces. There was a sound of many footsteps, and Alice looked round, eager to see the Queen.
Event: Alice witnesses the gardeners painting roses
ESummary: Alice encounters three gardeners frantically painting white roses red to avoid the Queen's wrath for having mistakenly planted a white rose. This strangely comical scene introduces the concept of fear and absurdity in the court.

Content: First came ten soldiers carrying clubs; these were all shaped like the three gardeners, oblong and flat, with their hands and feet at the corners: next the ten courtiers; these were ornamented all over with diamonds, and walked two and two, as the soldiers did. After these came the royal children; there were ten of them, and the little dears came jumping merrily along hand in hand, in couples: they were all ornamented with hearts. Next came the guests, mostly Kings and Queens, and among them Alice recognised the White Rabbit: it was talking in a hurried nervous manner, smiling at everything that was said, and went by without noticing her. Then followed the Knave of Hearts, carrying the King’s crown on a crimson velvet cushion; and, last of all this grand procession, came THE KING AND QUEEN OF HEARTS.
ESummary: A grand procession, including the Queen and King of Hearts, enters the garden. The sight creates a mixture of awe and trepidation for Alice, establishing the royal presence and setting the scene for ensuing conflicts.
CText: The White Rabbit hurried by Alice without noticing her.

Content: Alice was rather doubtful whether she ought not to lie down on her face like the three gardeners, but she could not remember ever having heard of such a rule at processions; “and besides, what would be the use of a procession,” thought she, “if people had all to lie down upon their faces, so that they couldn’t see it?” So she stood still where she was, and waited.
ESummary: A grand procession, including the Queen and King of Hearts, enters the garden. The sight creates a mixture of awe and trepidation for Alice, establishing the royal presence and setting the scene for ensuing conflicts.

Content: When the procession came opposite to Alice, they all stopped and looked at her, and the Queen said severely “Who is this?” She said it to the Knave of Hearts, who only bowed and smiled in reply.
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.

Content: “Idiot!” said the Queen, tossing her head impatiently; and, turning to Alice, she went on, “What’s your name, child?”
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.

Content: “My name is Alice, so please your Majesty,” said Alice very politely; but she added, to herself, “Why, they’re only a pack of cards, after all. I needn’t be afraid of them!”
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.
CText: Alice introduced herself to the Queen politely.

Content: “And who are _these?_” said the Queen, pointing to the three gardeners who were lying round the rose-tree; for, you see, as they were lying on their faces, and the pattern on their backs was the same as the rest of the pack, she could not tell whether they were gardeners, or soldiers, or courtiers, or three of her own children.
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.

Content: “How should _I_ know?” said Alice, surprised at her own courage. “It’s no business of _mine_.”
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.

Content: The Queen turned crimson with fury, and, after glaring at her for a moment like a wild beast, screamed “Off with her head! Off—”
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.
CText: The Queen ordered Alice's execution.

Content: “Nonsense!” said Alice, very loudly and decidedly, and the Queen was silent.
ESummary: The Queen questions Alice, who confidently claims her name. The Queen's annoyance foreshadows impending conflict, as she issues a severe command for Alice's beheading.

Content: The King laid his hand upon her arm, and timidly said “Consider, my dear: she is only a child!”
CText: The King defended Alice, stating she was only a child.

Content: The Queen turned angrily away from him, and said to the Knave “Turn them over!”
The Knave did so, very carefully, with one foot.
“Get up!” said the Queen, in a shrill, loud voice, and the three gardeners instantly jumped up, and began bowing to the King, the Queen, the royal children, and everybody else.
“Leave off that!” screamed the Queen. “You make me giddy.” And then, turning to the rose-tree, she went on, “What _have_ you been doing here?”
CText: The gardeners jumped up and bowed to the royalty after being commanded.

Content: “May it please your Majesty,” said Two, in a very humble tone, going down on one knee as he spoke, “we were trying—”

“_I_ see!” said the Queen, who had meanwhile been examining the roses. “Off with their heads!” and the procession moved on, three of the soldiers remaining behind to execute the unfortunate gardeners, who ran to Alice for protection.
ESummary: The three gardeners run to Alice for help when the Queen orders their execution. This event portrays the theme of authority and mercy as Alice intervenes to save them.

Content: “You shan’t be beheaded!” said Alice, and she put them into a large flower-pot that stood near. The three soldiers wandered about for a minute or two, looking for them, and then quietly marched off after the others.
ESummary: The three gardeners run to Alice for help when the Queen orders their execution. This event portrays the theme of authority and mercy as Alice intervenes to save them.
CText: Alice protected the gardeners from being executed.

Content: “Are their heads off?” shouted the Queen.
“Their heads are gone, if it please your Majesty!” the soldiers shouted in reply.
“That’s right!” shouted the Queen. “Can you play croquet?”
Event: The Queen challenges Alice to croquet
ESummary: The Queen invites Alice to join a game of croquet, further entangling Alice in the chaotic world of Wonderland, and emphasizing the absurdity of the Queen’s rule.

Content: “It’s—it’s a very fine day!” said a timid voice at her side. She was walking by the White Rabbit, who was peeping anxiously into her face.
“Very,” said Alice: “—where’s the Duchess?”

“Hush! Hush!” said the Rabbit in a low, hurried tone. He looked anxiously over his shoulder as he spoke, and then raised himself upon tiptoe, put his mouth close to her ear, and whispered “She’s under sentence of execution.”
CText: The White Rabbit whispered about the Duchess being under sentence of execution.

Content: “What for?” said Alice.
“Did you say ‘What a pity!’?” the Rabbit asked.
“No, I didn’t,” said Alice: “I don’t think it’s at all a pity. I said ‘What for?’”
CText: The Rabbit misunderstood Alice's inquiry about the Duchess.

Content: “She boxed the Queen’s ears—” the Rabbit began. Alice gave a little scream of laughter. “Oh, hush!” the Rabbit whispered in a frightened tone. “The Queen will hear you! You see, she came rather late, and the Queen said—”

“Get to your places!” shouted the Queen in a voice of thunder, and people began running about in all directions, tumbling up against each other; however, they got settled down in a minute or two, and the game began. Alice thought she had never seen such a curious croquet-ground in her life; it was all ridges and furrows; the balls were live hedgehogs, the mallets live flamingoes, and the soldiers had to double themselves up and to stand on their hands and feet, to make the arches.
Event: Game chaos and the Queen's fury
ESummary: The croquet game descends into confusion and chaos, illustrating the arbitrary nature of the Queen's authority and the danger Alice faces as tensions rise.

Content: The chief difficulty Alice found at first was in managing her flamingo: she succeeded in getting its body tucked away, comfortably enough, under her arm, with its legs hanging down, but generally, just as she had got its neck nicely straightened out, and was going to give the hedgehog a blow with its head, it _would_ twist itself round and look up in her face, with such a puzzled expression that she could not help bursting out laughing: and when she had got its head down, and was going to begin again, it was very provoking to find that the hedgehog had unrolled itself, and was in the act of crawling away: besides all this, there was generally a ridge or furrow in the way wherever she wanted to send the hedgehog to, and, as the doubled-up soldiers were always getting up and walking off to other parts of the ground, Alice soon came to the conclusion that it was a very difficult game indeed.
Event: Game chaos and the Queen's fury
ESummary: The croquet game descends into confusion and chaos, illustrating the arbitrary nature of the Queen's authority and the danger Alice faces as tensions rise.

Content: The players all played at once without waiting for turns, quarrelling all the while, and fighting for the hedgehogs; and in a very short time the Queen was in a furious passion, and went stamping about, and shouting “Off with his head!” or “Off with her head!” about once in a minute.
Event: Game chaos and the Queen's fury
ESummary: The croquet game descends into confusion and chaos, illustrating the arbitrary nature of the Queen's authority and the danger Alice faces as tensions rise.

Content: Alice began to feel very uneasy: to be sure, she had not as yet had any dispute with the Queen, but she knew that it might happen any minute, “and then,” thought she, “what would become of me? They’re dreadfully fond of beheading people here; the great wonder is, that there’s any one left alive!”
Event: Game chaos and the Queen's fury
ESummary: The croquet game descends into confusion and chaos, illustrating the arbitrary nature of the Queen's authority and the danger Alice faces as tensions rise.
CText: Alice worried about the possibility of being beheaded by the Queen.

Content: She was looking about for some way of escape, and wondering whether she could get away without being seen, when she noticed a curious appearance in the air: it puzzled her very much at first, but, after watching it a minute or two, she made it out to be a grin, and she said to herself “It’s the Cheshire Cat: now I shall have somebody to talk to.”
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who offers companionship and commentary on the bizarre happenings around her, marking a shift in Alice's navigation of Wonderland.

Content: “How are you getting on?” said the Cat, as soon as there was mouth enough for it to speak with.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who offers companionship and commentary on the bizarre happenings around her, marking a shift in Alice's navigation of Wonderland.
CText: The Cheshire Cat greeted Alice and asked how she was doing.

Content: Alice waited till the eyes appeared, and then nodded. “It’s no use speaking to it,” she thought, “till its ears have come, or at least one of them.” In another minute the whole head appeared, and then Alice put down her flamingo, and began an account of the game, feeling very glad she had someone to listen to her. The Cat seemed to think that there was enough of it now in sight, and no more of it appeared.
ESummary: Alice encounters the Cheshire Cat, who offers companionship and commentary on the bizarre happenings around her, marking a shift in Alice's navigation of Wonderland.

Content: “I don’t think they play at all fairly,” Alice began, in rather a complaining tone, “and they all quarrel so dreadfully one can’t hear oneself speak—and they don’t seem to have any rules in particular; at least, if there are, nobody attends to them—and you’ve no idea how confusing it is all the things being alive; for instance, there’s the arch I’ve got to go through next walking about at the other end of the ground—and I should have croqueted the Queen’s hedgehog just now, only it ran away when it saw mine coming!”
“How do you like the Queen?” said the Cat in a low voice.
CText: Alice complained about the unfairness of the game.

Content: “Not at all,” said Alice: “she’s so extremely—” Just then she noticed that the Queen was close behind her, listening: so she went on, “—likely to win, that it’s hardly worth while finishing the game.”
The Queen smiled and passed on.
CText: The Cat smiled and left when the Queen approached.

Content: “Who _are_ you talking to?” said the King, going up to Alice, and looking at the Cat’s head with great curiosity.
“It’s a friend of mine—a Cheshire Cat,” said Alice: “allow me to introduce it.”
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal
ESummary: The King brings Alice's attention to the Cheshire Cat, which the Queen demands be removed. The King eagerly goes to fetch the executioner.

Content: “I don’t like the look of it at all,” said the King: “however, it may kiss my hand if it likes.”
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal
CText: The King expressed his discomfort with the Cheshire Cat.

Content: “I’d rather not,” the Cat remarked.
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal

Content: “Don’t be impertinent,” said the King, “and don’t look at me like that!” He got behind Alice as he spoke.
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal

Content: “A cat may look at a king,” said Alice. “I’ve read that in some book, but I don’t remember where.”
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal

Content: “Well, it must be removed,” said the King very decidedly, and he called the Queen, who was passing at the moment, “My dear! I wish you would have this cat removed!”
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal

Content: The Queen had only one way of settling all difficulties, great or small. “Off with his head!” she said, without even looking round.
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal
CText: The Queen commanded for the Cheshire Cat to be removed.

Content: “I’ll fetch the executioner myself,” said the King eagerly, and he hurried off.
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal
CText: The King hurried off to find the executioner.

Content: Alice thought she might as well go back, and see how the game was going on, as she heard the Queen’s voice in the distance, screaming with passion. She had already heard her sentence three of the players to be executed for having missed their turns, and she did not like the look of things at all, as the game was in such confusion that she never knew whether it was her turn or not. So she went in search of her hedgehog.
Event: The Queen demands the Cheshire Cat's removal

Content: The hedgehog was engaged in a fight with another hedgehog, which seemed to Alice an excellent opportunity for croqueting one of them with the other: the only difficulty was, that her flamingo was gone across to the other side of the garden, where Alice could see it trying in a helpless sort of way to fly up into a tree.

By the time she had caught the flamingo and brought it back, the fight was over, and both the hedgehogs were out of sight: “but it doesn’t matter much,” thought Alice, “as all the arches are gone from this side of the ground.” So she tucked it away under her arm, that it might not escape again, and went back for a little more conversation with her friend.

When she got back to the Cheshire Cat, she was surprised to find quite a large crowd collected round it: there was a dispute going on between the executioner, the King, and the Queen, who were all talking at once, while all the rest were quite silent, and looked very uncomfortable.
Event: Alice mediates between the King, Queen, and executioner
ESummary: Alice is drawn into a humorous and chaotic argument about beheading, showcasing her growing confidence and the absurdity of the rules in Wonderland.

Content: The moment Alice appeared, she was appealed to by all three to settle the question, and they repeated their arguments to her, though, as they all spoke at once, she found it very hard indeed to make out exactly what they said.
Event: Alice mediates between the King, Queen, and executioner
ESummary: Alice is drawn into a humorous and chaotic argument about beheading, showcasing her growing confidence and the absurdity of the rules in Wonderland.
CText: The Cat's head faded away when the executioner went to fetch the Duchess.

Content: The executioner’s argument was, that you couldn’t cut off a head unless there was a body to cut it off from: that he had never had to do such a thing before, and he wasn’t going to begin at _his_ time of life.
Event: Alice mediates between the King, Queen, and executioner
ESummary: Alice is drawn into a humorous and chaotic argument about beheading, showcasing her growing confidence and the absurdity of the rules in Wonderland.

Content: The King’s argument was, that anything that had a head could be beheaded, and that you weren’t to talk nonsense.

ESummary: Alice is drawn into a humorous and chaotic argument about beheading, showcasing her growing confidence and the absurdity of the rules in Wonderland.

Content: The Queen’s argument was, that if something wasn’t done about it in less than no time she’d have everybody executed, all round. (It was this last remark that had made the whole party look so grave and anxious.)
Event: Alice mediates between the King, Queen, and executioner
ESummary: Alice is drawn into a humorous and chaotic argument about beheading, showcasing her growing confidence and the absurdity of the rules in Wonderland.

Content: Alice could think of nothing else to say but “It belongs to the Duchess: you’d better ask _her_ about it.”

Content: The Cat’s head began fading away the moment he was gone, and, by the time he had come back with the Duchess, it had entirely disappeared; so the King and the executioner ran wildly up and down looking for it, while the rest of the party went back to the game.

Content: CHAPTER IX. The Mock Turtle’s Story
“You can’t think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing!” said the Duchess, as she tucked her arm affectionately into Alice’s, and they walked off together.
ESummary: Alice is delighted to see the Duchess in a happy mood, contrasting her earlier aggression. This moment highlights the theme of transformation and indicates that circumstances can change a person's disposition.
CText: The Duchess tucks her arm affectionately into Alice's.

Content: Alice was very glad to find her in such a pleasant temper, and thought to herself that perhaps it was only the pepper that had made her so savage when they met in the kitchen.
ESummary: Alice is delighted to see the Duchess in a happy mood, contrasting her earlier aggression. This moment highlights the theme of transformation and indicates that circumstances can change a person's disposition.

Content: “When _I’m_ a Duchess,” she said to herself, (not in a very hopeful tone though), “I won’t have any pepper in my kitchen _at all_. Soup does very well without—Maybe it’s always pepper that makes people hot-tempered,” she went on, very much pleased at having found out a new kind of rule, “and vinegar that makes them sour—and camomile that makes them bitter—and—and barley-sugar and such things that make children sweet-tempered. I only wish people knew _that_: then they wouldn’t be so stingy about it, you know—”
ESummary: Alice is delighted to see the Duchess in a happy mood, contrasting her earlier aggression. This moment highlights the theme of transformation and indicates that circumstances can change a person's disposition.
CText: Alice thinks about the effects of various ingredients on people's temperaments.

Content: She had quite forgotten the Duchess by this time, and was a little startled when she heard her voice close to her ear. “You’re thinking about something, my dear, and that makes you forget to talk. I can’t tell you just now what the moral of that is, but I shall remember it in a bit.”
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “Perhaps it hasn’t one,” Alice ventured to remark.
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “Tut, tut, child!” said the Duchess. “Everything’s got a moral, if only you can find it.” And she squeezed herself up closer to Alice’s side as she spoke.
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.
CText: The Duchess insists that everything has a moral.

Content: Alice did not much like keeping so close to her: first, because the Duchess was _very_ ugly; and secondly, because she was exactly the right height to rest her chin upon Alice’s shoulder, and it was an uncomfortably sharp chin. However, she did not like to be rude, so she bore it as well as she could.
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “The game’s going on rather better now,” she said, by way of keeping up the conversation a little.
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “’Tis so,” said the Duchess: “and the moral of that is—‘Oh, ’tis love, ’tis love, that makes the world go round!’”
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.
CText: Alice acknowledges the Duchess's remark about love.

Content: “Somebody said,” Alice whispered, “that it’s done by everybody minding their own business!”
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “Ah, well! It means much the same thing,” said the Duchess, digging her sharp little chin into Alice’s shoulder as she added, “and the moral of _that_ is—‘Take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of themselves.’”
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “How fond she is of finding morals in things!” Alice thought to herself.
ESummary: The Duchess ponders the morals behind different feelings and flavors, suggesting that different emotions can be associated with various foods. This introduces a playful philosophical element to their conversation.

Content: “I dare say you’re wondering why I don’t put my arm round your waist,” the Duchess said after a pause: “the reason is, that I’m doubtful about the temper of your flamingo. Shall I try the experiment?”
CText: The Duchess explains her reasoning for not putting her arm around Alice.

Content: “He might bite,” Alice cautiously replied, not feeling at all anxious to have the experiment tried.
“Very true,” said the Duchess: “flamingoes and mustard both bite. And the moral of that is—‘Birds of a feather flock together.’”
“Only mustard isn’t a bird,” Alice remarked.
“Right, as usual,” said the Duchess: “what a clear way you have of putting things!”
CText: Alice appreciates the Duchess's clarity in expressing ideas.

Content: “It’s a mineral, I _think_,” said Alice.

“Of course it is,” said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to everything that Alice said; “there’s a large mustard-mine near here. And the moral of that is—‘The more there is of mine, the less there is of yours.’”
“Oh, I know!” exclaimed Alice, who had not attended to this last remark, “it’s a vegetable. It doesn’t look like one, but it is.”

“I quite agree with you,” said the Duchess; “and the moral of that is—‘Be what you would seem to be’—or if you’d like it put more simply—‘Never imagine yourself not to be otherwise than what it might appear to others that what you were or might have been was not otherwise than what you had been would have appeared to them to be otherwise.’”
“I think I should understand that better,” Alice said very politely, “if I had it written down: but I can’t quite follow it as you say it.”
“That’s nothing to what I could say if I chose,” the Duchess replied, in a pleased tone.
“Pray don’t trouble yourself to say it any longer than that,” said Alice.
“Oh, don’t talk about trouble!” said the Duchess. “I make you a present of everything I’ve said as yet.”
CText: The Duchess dismisses Alice's concerns about trouble.

Content: “A cheap sort of present!” thought Alice. “I’m glad they don’t give birthday presents like that!” But she did not venture to say it out loud.
“Thinking again?” the Duchess asked, with another dig of her sharp little chin.
“I’ve a right to think,” said Alice sharply, for she was beginning to feel a little worried.
“Just about as much right,” said the Duchess, “as pigs have to fly; and the m—”

But here, to Alice’s great surprise, the Duchess’s voice died away, even in the middle of her favourite word ‘moral,’ and the arm that was linked into hers began to tremble. Alice looked up, and there stood the Queen in front of them, with her arms folded, frowning like a thunderstorm.
ESummary: The Queen appears, threatening the Duchess with execution. This sudden shift in tone establishes the Queen's tyrannical nature and sets a tone of danger, foreshadowing the chaos to come.
CText: Alice is startled when she hears the Duchess's voice close to her ear.

Content: “A fine day, your Majesty!” the Duchess began in a low, weak voice.
ESummary: The Queen appears, threatening the Duchess with execution. This sudden shift in tone establishes the Queen's tyrannical nature and sets a tone of danger, foreshadowing the chaos to come.

Content: “Now, I give you fair warning,” shouted the Queen, stamping on the ground as she spoke; “either you or your head must be off, and that in about half no time! Take your choice!”
ESummary: The Queen appears, threatening the Duchess with execution. This sudden shift in tone establishes the Queen's tyrannical nature and sets a tone of danger, foreshadowing the chaos to come.
CText: The Queen threatens the Duchess with losing her head.

Content: The Duchess took her choice, and was gone in a moment.
ESummary: The Duchess chooses her fate and is executed by the Queen. This stark moment underscores the arbitrary cruelty of the Queen's rule and raises the stakes for Alice.

Content: “Let’s go on with the game,” the Queen said to Alice; and Alice was too much frightened to say a word, but slowly followed her back to the croquet-ground.

The other guests had taken advantage of the Queen’s absence, and were resting in the shade: however, the moment they saw her, they hurried back to the game, the Queen merely remarking that a moment’s delay would cost them their lives.
CText: The Queen orders the game to continue despite the chaos.

Content: All the time they were playing the Queen never left off quarrelling with the other players, and shouting “Off with his head!” or “Off with her head!” Those whom she sentenced were taken into custody by the soldiers, who of course had to leave off being arches to do this, so that by the end of half an hour or so there were no arches left, and all the players, except the King, the Queen, and Alice, were in custody and under sentence of execution.
Then the Queen left off, quite out of breath, and said to Alice, “Have you seen the Mock Turtle yet?”
Event: Alice is taken to see the Mock Turtle
ESummary: After the Duchess’s execution, the Queen takes Alice to meet the Mock Turtle, signaling a change in Alice’s journey and setting the stage for further whimsical encounters.
CText: The Queen inquires if Alice has seen the Mock Turtle.

Content: “No,” said Alice. “I don’t even know what a Mock Turtle is.”
Event: Alice is taken to see the Mock Turtle
ESummary: After the Duchess’s execution, the Queen takes Alice to meet the Mock Turtle, signaling a change in Alice’s journey and setting the stage for further whimsical encounters.

Content: “It’s the thing Mock Turtle Soup is made from,” said the Queen.
Event: Alice is taken to see the Mock Turtle
ESummary: After the Duchess’s execution, the Queen takes Alice to meet the Mock Turtle, signaling a change in Alice’s journey and setting the stage for further whimsical encounters.

Content: “I never saw one, or heard of one,” said Alice.
Event: Alice is taken to see the Mock Turtle
ESummary: After the Duchess’s execution, the Queen takes Alice to meet the Mock Turtle, signaling a change in Alice’s journey and setting the stage for further whimsical encounters.

Content: “Come on, then,” said the Queen, “and he shall tell you his history,”
Event: Alice is taken to see the Mock Turtle
ESummary: After the Duchess’s execution, the Queen takes Alice to meet the Mock Turtle, signaling a change in Alice’s journey and setting the stage for further whimsical encounters.
CText: The Queen decides to lead Alice to the Mock Turtle.

Content: As they walked off together, Alice heard the King say in a low voice, to the company generally, “You are all pardoned.” “Come, _that’s_ a good thing!” she said to herself, for she had felt quite unhappy at the number of executions the Queen had ordered.

They very soon came upon a Gryphon, lying fast asleep in the sun. (If you don’t know what a Gryphon is, look at the picture.) “Up, lazy thing!” said the Queen, “and take this young lady to see the Mock Turtle, and to hear his history. I must go back and see after some executions I have ordered;” and she walked off, leaving Alice alone with the Gryphon. Alice did not quite like the look of the creature, but on the whole she thought it would be quite as safe to stay with it as to go after that savage Queen: so she waited.
ESummary: Alice meets the Gryphon, who offers a mix of light-heartedness and mischief. This character adds depth to the narrative and introduces a whimsical guide for Alice.
CText: The Gryphon wakes up and chuckles at the situation.

Content: The Gryphon sat up and rubbed its eyes: then it watched the Queen till she was out of sight: then it chuckled. “What fun!” said the Gryphon, half to itself, half to Alice.
“What _is_ the fun?” said Alice.
“Why, _she_,” said the Gryphon. “It’s all her fancy, that: they never executes nobody, you know. Come on!”
CText: The Gryphon explains that the Queen's threats are just a fancy.

Content: “Everybody says ‘come on!’ here,” thought Alice, as she went slowly after it: “I never was so ordered about in all my life, never!”

They had not gone far before they saw the Mock Turtle in the distance, sitting sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock, and, as they came nearer, Alice could hear him sighing as if his heart would break. She pitied him deeply. “What is his sorrow?” she asked the Gryphon, and the Gryphon answered, very nearly in the same words as before, “It’s all his fancy, that: he hasn’t got no sorrow, you know. Come on!”
ESummary: Alice arrives with the Gryphon to see the Mock Turtle, who sits forlornly. This encounter promises to uncover a new aspect of Wonderland's lore and characters.

Content: So they went up to the Mock Turtle, who looked at them with large eyes full of tears, but said nothing.
ESummary: Alice arrives with the Gryphon to see the Mock Turtle, who sits forlornly. This encounter promises to uncover a new aspect of Wonderland's lore and characters.
CText: The Mock Turtle looks at Alice and the Gryphon with tears in his eyes.

Content: “This here young lady,” said the Gryphon, “she wants for to know your history, she do.”
“I’ll tell it her,” said the Mock Turtle in a deep, hollow tone: “sit down, both of you, and don’t speak a word till I’ve finished.”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle begins to recount his story while displaying signs of regret and despondency. This moment invites curiosity and concern about his past.

Content: So they sat down, and nobody spoke for some minutes. Alice thought to herself, “I don’t see how he can _ever_ finish, if he doesn’t begin.” But she waited patiently.
ESummary: The Mock Turtle begins to recount his story while displaying signs of regret and despondency. This moment invites curiosity and concern about his past.

Content: “Once,” said the Mock Turtle at last, with a deep sigh, “I was a real Turtle.”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle begins to recount his story while displaying signs of regret and despondency. This moment invites curiosity and concern about his past.
CText: The Mock Turtle reveals he was once a real Turtle.

Content: These words were followed by a very long silence, broken only by an occasional exclamation of “Hjckrrh!” from the Gryphon, and the constant heavy sobbing of the Mock Turtle. Alice was very nearly getting up and saying, “Thank you, sir, for your interesting story,” but she could not help thinking there _must_ be more to come, so she sat still and said nothing.

“When we were little,” the Mock Turtle went on at last, more calmly, though still sobbing a little now and then, “we went to school in the sea. The master was an old Turtle—we used to call him Tortoise—”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle shares details about his schooling under a 'Tortoise', illustrating the absurdity of Wonderland's educational system. This adds humor and depth to his character.

Content: “Why did you call him Tortoise, if he wasn’t one?” Alice asked.
ESummary: The Mock Turtle shares details about his schooling under a 'Tortoise', illustrating the absurdity of Wonderland's educational system. This adds humor and depth to his character.

Content: “We called him Tortoise because he taught us,” said the Mock Turtle angrily: “really you are very dull!”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle shares details about his schooling under a 'Tortoise', illustrating the absurdity of Wonderland's educational system. This adds humor and depth to his character.

Content: “You ought to be ashamed of yourself for asking such a simple question,” added the Gryphon; and then they both sat silent and looked at poor Alice, who felt ready to sink into the earth. At last the Gryphon said to the Mock Turtle, “Drive on, old fellow! Don’t be all day about it!” and he went on in these words:
ESummary: The Mock Turtle shares details about his schooling under a 'Tortoise', illustrating the absurdity of Wonderland's educational system. This adds humor and depth to his character.
CText: The Gryphon urges the Mock Turtle to continue his story.

Content: “Yes, we went to school in the sea, though you mayn’t believe it—”
“I never said I didn’t!” interrupted Alice.
“You did,” said the Mock Turtle.
“Hold your tongue!” added the Gryphon, before Alice could speak again. The Mock Turtle went on.
“We had the best of educations—in fact, we went to school every day—”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school
ESummary: The Mock Turtle discusses the subjects he learned at school, including 'Reeling and Writhing' and 'Uglification.' This bizarre curriculum highlights the nonsensical nature of the story.
CText: The Mock Turtle explains their school experiences under the sea.

Content: “_I’ve_ been to a day-school, too,” said Alice; “you needn’t be so proud as all that.”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “With extras?” asked the Mock Turtle a little anxiously.
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “Yes,” said Alice, “we learned French and music.”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “And washing?” said the Mock Turtle.
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “Certainly not!” said Alice indignantly.
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “Ah! then yours wasn’t a really good school,” said the Mock Turtle in a tone of great relief. “Now at _ours_ they had at the end of the bill, ‘French, music, _and washing_—extra.’”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school
CText: The Mock Turtle describes the subjects of his education.

Content: “You couldn’t have wanted it much,” said Alice; “living at the bottom of the sea.”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “I couldn’t afford to learn it.” said the Mock Turtle with a sigh. “I only took the regular course.”
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “What was that?” inquired Alice.
Event: Curriculum of the Mock Turtle's school

Content: “Reeling and Writhing, of course, to begin with,” the Mock Turtle replied; “and then the different branches of Arithmetic—Ambition, Distraction, Uglification, and Derision.”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle describes various ridiculous subjects he studied, including 'Uglification.' This conversation emphasizes the nonsensical nature of Wonderland and deepens the theme of absurdity in education.

Content: “I never heard of ‘Uglification,’” Alice ventured to say. “What is it?”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle describes various ridiculous subjects he studied, including 'Uglification.' This conversation emphasizes the nonsensical nature of Wonderland and deepens the theme of absurdity in education.

Content: The Gryphon lifted up both its paws in surprise. “What! Never heard of uglifying!” it exclaimed. “You know what to beautify is, I suppose?”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle describes various ridiculous subjects he studied, including 'Uglification.' This conversation emphasizes the nonsensical nature of Wonderland and deepens the theme of absurdity in education.

Content: “Yes,” said Alice doubtfully: “it means—to—make—anything—prettier.”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle describes various ridiculous subjects he studied, including 'Uglification.' This conversation emphasizes the nonsensical nature of Wonderland and deepens the theme of absurdity in education.

Content: “Well, then,” the Gryphon went on, “if you don’t know what to uglify is, you _are_ a simpleton.”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle describes various ridiculous subjects he studied, including 'Uglification.' This conversation emphasizes the nonsensical nature of Wonderland and deepens the theme of absurdity in education.

Content: Alice did not feel encouraged to ask any more questions about it, so she turned to the Mock Turtle, and said “What else had you to learn?”

“Well, there was Mystery,” the Mock Turtle replied, counting off the subjects on his flappers, “—Mystery, ancient and modern, with Seaography: then Drawling—the Drawling-master was an old conger-eel, that used to come once a week: _he_ taught us Drawling, Stretching, and Fainting in Coils.”
“What was _that_ like?” said Alice.
“Well, I can’t show it you myself,” the Mock Turtle said: “I’m too stiff. And the Gryphon never learnt it.”
“Hadn’t time,” said the Gryphon: “I went to the Classics master, though. He was an old crab, _he_ was.”
ESummary: The Gryphon adds to the jest by commenting on Alice's ignorance and engaging in playful banter with the Mock Turtle. This interaction highlights the camaraderie among characters in a whimsical context.
CText: The Gryphon shares that he went to a Classics master.

Content: “I never went to him,” the Mock Turtle said with a sigh: “he taught Laughing and Grief, they used to say.”
ESummary: The Gryphon adds to the jest by commenting on Alice's ignorance and engaging in playful banter with the Mock Turtle. This interaction highlights the camaraderie among characters in a whimsical context.

Content: “So he did, so he did,” said the Gryphon, sighing in his turn; and both creatures hid their faces in their paws.
ESummary: The Gryphon adds to the jest by commenting on Alice's ignorance and engaging in playful banter with the Mock Turtle. This interaction highlights the camaraderie among characters in a whimsical context.

Content: “And how many hours a day did you do lessons?” said Alice, in a hurry to change the subject.
ESummary: Alice learns more about the peculiar education at the Mock Turtle's school, including the peculiarities of lesson plans that 'lessen' from day to day. This conversation brings lightness to the previous heavy atmosphere.

Content: “Ten hours the first day,” said the Mock Turtle: “nine the next, and so on.”
ESummary: Alice inquires about the Mock Turtle's lessons, leading to an even sillier discussion about the structure of their education. This reflects the playful nature of Wonderland while emphasizing its illogical rules.

Content: “What a curious plan!” exclaimed Alice.
ESummary: Alice inquires about the Mock Turtle's lessons, leading to an even sillier discussion about the structure of their education. This reflects the playful nature of Wonderland while emphasizing its illogical rules.

Content: “That’s the reason they’re called lessons,” the Gryphon remarked: “because they lessen from day to day.”
ESummary: Alice inquires about the Mock Turtle's lessons, leading to an even sillier discussion about the structure of their education. This reflects the playful nature of Wonderland while emphasizing its illogical rules.

Content: This was quite a new idea to Alice, and she thought it over a little before she made her next remark. “Then the eleventh day must have been a holiday?”
ESummary: Alice inquires about the Mock Turtle's lessons, leading to an even sillier discussion about the structure of their education. This reflects the playful nature of Wonderland while emphasizing its illogical rules.

Content: “Of course it was,” said the Mock Turtle.
ESummary: Alice inquires about the Mock Turtle's lessons, leading to an even sillier discussion about the structure of their education. This reflects the playful nature of Wonderland while emphasizing its illogical rules.

Content: “And how did you manage on the twelfth?” Alice went on eagerly.

Content: “That’s enough about lessons,” the Gryphon interrupted in a very decided tone: “tell her something about the games now.”
CHAPTER X. The Lobster Quadrille
ESummary: The Mock Turtle expresses deep sadness, struggling to speak due to sobs while the Gryphon tries to comfort him. This moment highlights the Mock Turtle's emotional state and sets the comedic tone of the upcoming conversation.

Content: The Mock Turtle sighed deeply, and drew the back of one flapper across his eyes. He looked at Alice, and tried to speak, but for a minute or two sobs choked his voice. “Same as if he had a bone in his throat,” said the Gryphon: and it set to work shaking him and punching him in the back. At last the Mock Turtle recovered his voice, and, with tears running down his cheeks, he went on again:—
ESummary: The Mock Turtle expresses deep sadness, struggling to speak due to sobs while the Gryphon tries to comfort him. This moment highlights the Mock Turtle's emotional state and sets the comedic tone of the upcoming conversation.
CText: The Gryphon shakes and punches the Mock Turtle to help him recover his voice.

Content: “You may not have lived much under the sea—” (“I haven’t,” said Alice)—“and perhaps you were never even introduced to a lobster—” (Alice began to say “I once tasted—” but checked herself hastily, and said “No, never”) “—so you can have no idea what a delightful thing a Lobster Quadrille is!”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle introduces the concept of the Lobster Quadrille, a whimsical dance involving sea creatures. This sets the stage for an exploration of the fantastical elements in the characters' world and Alice's curiosity.
CText: He mentions the delightful nature of the Lobster Quadrille.

Content: “No, indeed,” said Alice. “What sort of a dance is it?”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle introduces the concept of the Lobster Quadrille, a whimsical dance involving sea creatures. This sets the stage for an exploration of the fantastical elements in the characters' world and Alice's curiosity.
CText: Alice asks about the Lobster Quadrille and expresses her wish to see it.

Content: “Why,” said the Gryphon, “you first form into a line along the sea-shore—”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle introduces the concept of the Lobster Quadrille, a whimsical dance involving sea creatures. This sets the stage for an exploration of the fantastical elements in the characters' world and Alice's curiosity.

Content: “Two lines!” cried the Mock Turtle. “Seals, turtles, salmon, and so on; then, when you’ve cleared all the jelly-fish out of the way—”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle introduces the concept of the Lobster Quadrille, a whimsical dance involving sea creatures. This sets the stage for an exploration of the fantastical elements in the characters' world and Alice's curiosity.

Content: “_That_ generally takes some time,” interrupted the Gryphon.

Content: “—you advance twice—”
ESummary: The Mock Turtle introduces the concept of the Lobster Quadrille, a whimsical dance involving sea creatures. This sets the stage for an exploration of the fantastical elements in the characters' world and Alice's curiosity.

Content: “Each with a lobster as a partner!” cried the Gryphon.

Content: “—as far out to sea as you can—”
ESummary: The characters describe the elaborate steps of the Lobster Quadrille, filled with absurdity and humor. This showcases the surreal nature of Alice's experiences and deepens her engagement with this peculiar world.

Content: “Swim after them!” screamed the Gryphon.
ESummary: The characters describe the elaborate steps of the Lobster Quadrille, filled with absurdity and humor. This showcases the surreal nature of Alice's experiences and deepens her engagement with this peculiar world.

Content: “Turn a somersault in the sea!” cried the Mock Turtle, capering wildly about.

Content: “Change lobsters again!” yelled the Gryphon at the top of its voice.
